article.headline: All-American 11 of 11 from the field
article.linkText: LSU rides perfect Augustus past North Texas
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Seimone Augustus didn't realize she had
such a perfect night.

Augustus scored 22 points on 11-for-11 shooting from the field,
leading No. 1 LSU to a 77-51 victory over North Texas on Tuesday
night.

"Really?" Augustus said when told of her flawless shooting
night. "It was just the same old, same old. It just came within
our offense. I got a couple of easy baskets off our press."

Freshman Sylvia Fowles had 13 points and 11 rebounds for her
third double-double in five games for the Tigers (8-0), who are
ranked No. 1 for the first time since 1978 and off to their best
start in two years.

Talicia Sanders led North Texas (2-2) with 12 points, Erika Bobo
had 11 points and Mian Williams added 10.

The Tigers had an easy time with the overmatched Mean Green,
leading by as much as 27 points before coach Pokey Chatman cleared
the bench with almost five minutes remaining. Every LSU player got
into the game.

Augustus, averaging 20.7 points a game, and Scholanda Hoston
combined to score 24 points in the first half, while North Texas
managed just 25

Despite the victory, neither the LSU players or coach were happy
with the game.

"It's good we won and good we're undefeated, but us winning and
being undefeated is not going to get us where we want to go with
the schedule we have," Temeka Johnson said. "It's good for us to
win and come out ahead, but if we're not executing the way we're
capable of executing, it doesn't mean anything."

LSU's offense was the problem, Chatman said.

"North Texas came in and took us out of our half-court offense
and that's something we pride ourselves in," Chatman said. "We
had a lot of spurts, some good spurts, but not a lot of offensive
execution."

The Tigers hit a rough stretch opening the second half, scoring
only one basket in the first six minutes. North Texas cut LSU's
lead to 13 before Johnson hit a layup to make it 47-32. It was the
closest the Mean Green would come.

"We struggled a little bit coming out," Hoston said. "The
energy was there -- we just didn't do as good a job as we can
executing."

But if the LSU offense was not what Chatman wanted, the defense
was.

North Texas scored the first basket of the game then did not
make another until Natalie Mireles hit a 3-pointer almost five
minutes later. The basket stopped a 16-2 run by the Tigers, who led
16-5. LSU forced six turnovers during the run, 17 during the first
half, a season-high 29 for the game.

The Tigers, who led 41-25 at halftime, had 22 steals -- compared
to eight for North Texas.

"They have a lot of depth and weapons," North Texas coach Tina
Slinker said. "It makes it really hard to concentrate on one
player. I just wish we could have shot the ball better."

The Tigers scored 28 points off turnovers and 12 fast-break
points.

"Our pressure was the high-scorer for us tonight," Chatman
said. "We had 28 points off turnovers. Thank goodness we were able
to do that because we didn't quite execute in the half court."
